Drift's output has three distinct consumer types, each with fundamentally different needs: interactive humans at a terminal (need legible, scannable output with visual cues), humans piping output to other tools or files (need clean text without escape codes), and software consuming drift programmatically (need structured data, not prose to regex-parse). A single output format cannot serve all three simultaneously. See <ref spec="open_source_tools_drift.dual_audience_constraint">the dual audience constraint</ref>.